From: &quot;sem_antico&quot; &lt;rest-discuss@...&gt;

&gt; Another popular use of cookies is as an alternative authentication
&gt; mechanism. The chief motivation for this is the lack of control most
&gt; user agents give application designers over the standard http
&gt; authorisation mechanisms - no easy way of providing customised login
&gt; prompts and no control over expiring authentication are two of the
&gt; issues here. Does this application of cookies break REST principles?

If one of the REST principles is visibility into messages for key
information - like authentication - then moving authentication out of the
standard header and into custom cookies would then violate this aspect.

I found a Note on the W3C site about extending HTML FORM with authentication
information - this would allow application authors to declare their usage of
authentication in a way that provides control over the user experience as
well as allowing the user-agent to correctly translate that into protocol
level authentication.

http://www.w3.org/TR/NOTE-authentform

---an example---
&lt;AUTHFORM&gt;
User Name: &lt;INPUT TYPE=AUTHUSER&gt;&lt;BR&gt;
Password:  &lt;INPUT TYPE=AUTHSECRET&gt;&lt;BR&gt;
Realm:     &lt;SELECT TYPE=AUTHREALM&gt;
             &lt;OPTION VALUE=READONLY SELECTED&gt;Read Only&lt;/OPTION&gt;
             &lt;OPTION VALUE=READWRITE&gt;Read/Write&lt;/OPTION&gt;
           &lt;/SELECT&gt;&lt;BR&gt;
&lt;INPUT TYPE=AUTHLOAD VALUE=&quot;Log In&quot;&gt;
&lt;INPUT TYPE=AUTHUNLOAD  VALUE=&quot;Log Out&quot;&gt;
&lt;/AUTHFORM&gt;
---an example---
